Optimizing Sparse Generalized Singular Vectors for Feature Selection in Proximal Support Vector Machines with Application to Breast and Ovarian Cancer Detection

Ugochukwu O. Ugwu Corresponding author: Ugochukwu.Ugwu@tufts.edu, uugobinnah@gmail.com Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering, Tufts University, Medford, MA 02155, USA Michael Kirby Department of Mathematics, Colorado State University, CO 80523, USA
Abstract

This paper presents approaches to compute sparse solutions of Generalized Singular Value Problem (GSVP). The GSVP is regularized by â„“1subscriptâ„“1\ell_{1}roman_â„“ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT-norm and â„“qsubscriptâ„“ğ‘\ell_{q}roman_â„“ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_q end_POSTSUBSCRIPT-penalty for 0<q<10ğ‘10<q<10 < italic_q < 1, resulting in the â„“1subscriptâ„“1\ell_{1}roman_â„“ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT-GSVP and â„“qsubscriptâ„“ğ‘\ell_{q}roman_â„“ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_q end_POSTSUBSCRIPT-GSVP formulations. The solutions of these problems are determined by applying the proximal gradient descent algorithm with a fixed step size. The inherent sparsity levels within the computed solutions are exploited for feature selection, and subsequently, binary classification with non-parallel Support Vector Machines (SVM). For our feature selection task, SVM is integrated into the â„“1subscriptâ„“1\ell_{1}roman_â„“ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT-GSVP and â„“qsubscriptâ„“ğ‘\ell_{q}roman_â„“ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_q end_POSTSUBSCRIPT-GSVP frameworks to derive the â„“1subscriptâ„“1\ell_{1}roman_â„“ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT-GSVPSVM and â„“qsubscriptâ„“ğ‘\ell_{q}roman_â„“ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_q end_POSTSUBSCRIPT-GSVPSVM variants. Machine learning applications to cancer detection are considered. We remarkably report near-to-perfect balanced accuracy across breast and ovarian cancer datasets using a few selected features.

Key words: binary classification, data integration, feature selection, machine learning, optimization, sparse generalized singular vectors, support vector machine, regularization

The use of â„“1subscriptâ„“1\ell_{1}roman_â„“ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT-norm in (1.4) is to promote sparsity in the computed (approximate) generalized singular vectors. As such, only the non-zero elements of ğ³isubscriptğ³ğ‘–\mathbf{z}_{i}bold_z start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT are utilized for feature selection. The sparsity enhancing property of â„“1subscriptâ„“1\ell_{1}roman_â„“ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT penalty has been widely adopted in the literature; see, e.g., [32, 6], but the novelty of our contributions lie in its application in the context of (1.4).

It is the purpose of this paper to develop new strategies for computing sparse solutions of (1.1), and then discuss how sparsity in the computed solutions can be exploited to carry out feature selection and binary classification tasks. In our specific applications, such as microarray data analysis, the number of non-zero elements in the solutions of (1.4) directly correspond to the most relevant and informative genes in A1subscriptğ´1A_{1}italic_A start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and A2subscriptğ´2A_{2}italic_A start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, while genes associated with â€œnear-zeroâ€ coefficients are considered irrelevant or redundant. When the solutions of (1.4) are very sparse, only a small number of features will be selected. This drastically reduces the dimensionality of the data matrices, resulting in improved robustness to noise, as well as the accuracy and efficiency of subsequent analyses, such as breast and ovarian cancer classification.

The GSVD (without â„“1subscriptâ„“1\ell_{1}roman_â„“ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT penalty) has been extensively employed for gene selection purposes in the literature; see, e.g., [2, 4]. In particular, a gene shaving [17] approach described in [4] focuses on selecting the most variant genes across several cancer cell lines and tumor samples. This method iteratively projects each gene onto a chosen projection direction determined by the generalized singular values. Then progressively shaves off the least variant group of genes with the smallest positive and negative projection scores. It is noteworthy that the utilization of the GSVD projections in a non-iterative manner, for gene selection and simultaneous low-rank reconstruction of gene expression datasets, was first proposed in [2]. An extension of this idea to higher-order GSVD for gene selection is presented in, e.g., [27, 23].

We are also interested in computing approximate solutions of (1.1) with a greater degree of sparsity than in (1.4). This is motivated by our desire to determine a parsimonious set of predictive features (genes) that will provide better insight into the biological mechanism at play in the host response to infections. 1.1 A Review of Related Methods

To the best of our knowledge, we are the first to develop and apply the â„“qsubscriptâ„“ğ‘\ell_{q}roman_â„“ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_q end_POSTSUBSCRIPT-PGD-GSVPSVM framework for the solutions of (1.4) and (1.5). However, the integration of SVM into the generalized Rayleigh quotients (1.1) is not new. The idea was first proposed in a seminal work by Mangasarian and Wild [20] and referred to as the Generalized Eigenvalue Proximal SVM (GEPSVM).

The GEPSVM regularizes the numerator of (1.1) with a squared â„“2subscriptâ„“2\ell_{2}roman_â„“ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT-norm. 6 Conclusions

We have demonstrated that the â„“qsubscriptâ„“ğ‘\ell_{q}roman_â„“ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_q end_POSTSUBSCRIPT-PGD-GSVPSVM methods for 0<qâ‰¤10ğ‘10<q\leq 10 < italic_q â‰¤ 1 are viable feature selection and classification techniques that can achieve perfect to near-perfect classification accuracy. The performance of the methods are illustrated using the breast and ovarian cancer datasets. The sparsity levels in the computed solutions are exploited to select a parsimonious set of informative features. For the â„“qsubscriptâ„“ğ‘\ell_{q}roman_â„“ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_q end_POSTSUBSCRIPT-PGD-GSVPSVM method, smaller values of qğ‘qitalic_q often result in fewer features being selected.
